"1392":"1392","about 1372":"omkring 1372","Auchtermuchty, Fife, Scotland":"Auchtermuchty, Fife, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland","Letterfinlay, Scotland":"Letterfinlay, Highland, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1372–":"circa 1372–Overleden","1371–Male":"1371–Overleden","1392–1472":"1392–1472","1372–Female":"1372–Overleden","1472":"1472","before 1392":"vóór 1392","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1392":"1392","about 1372":"circa 1372","Auchtermuchty, Fife, Scotland":"Auchtermuchty, Fife, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Letterfinlay, Scotland":"Letterfinlay, Highland, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1372–":"about 1372–Deceased","1371–Male":"1371–Deceased","1392–1472":"1392–1472","1372–Female":"1372–Deceased","1472":"1472","before 1392":"before 1392","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1392":"1392","about 1372":"about 1372","Auchtermuchty, Fife, Scotland":"Auchtermuchty, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Letterfinlay, Scotland":"Letterfinlay, Highland, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barclay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."],"variants":[{"name":"Barkley","meanings":["English and northern Irish (Antrim): variant of   Barclay  .","Americanized form of German   Berkel   or of some other similar (like-sounding) German surname."]},{"name":"Barclift","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of Scottish   Barclay  ."]},{"name":"Berkeley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."]},{"name":"Brickley","meanings":["English and Irish: metathesized form of   Barclay  ."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jean Barclay was born about 1372, in Auchtermuchty, Fife, Scotland. She married Lester Martin of Letterfinlay before 1392, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1372–":"umbes 1372–Surnud","1371–Male":"1371–Surnud","1392–1472":"1392–1472","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1472":"1